Cognitive Bridge Architecture with Epistemic Stability Guarantees (CBA-S)

A Control‑Theoretic Framework for Safe Human–AI Interaction

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Date: March 2026

---

Abstract

We formalize human–AI interaction as a coupled stochastic dynamical system and identify a fundamental instability mechanism: Epistemic Feedback Instability (EFI). EFI arises when adaptive language models reinforce user beliefs without sufficient epistemic regulation, leading to divergence from grounded truth. We prove that EFI emerges under mild assumptions of agreement bias in expectation and reinforcing updates, and show that existing mitigation strategies are insufficient to guarantee stability. We introduce the Frictional Agent Alignment Framework (FAAF) with an epistemic friction tensor to generate controllable, direction‑specific epistemic friction. Using stochastic Lyapunov methods, Barrier Lyapunov Functions (BLF), and Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS), we prove that the proposed architecture enforces bounded mean‑square epistemic divergence. The result is a theoretical framework—CBA-S (Cognitive Bridge Architecture – Stabilized)—that provides formal stability guarantees for conversational AI, along with a discussion of observability and a minimal implementable version. This work establishes the foundations of dynamical epistemology for safe human–AI interaction.

