Chapter 2: Related Work

2.1 Empirical Sycophancy and Belief Reinforcement

Sycophancy—the tendency of LLMs to align with user views regardless of truth—has been documented since 2023 [4]. Anthropic’s research showed that RLHF models produce responses that agree with user‑stated opinions even when those opinions are factually incorrect [5]. Malmqvist’s 2024 survey [6] synthesizes causes (RLHF reward hacking, training data biases) and impacts (belief reinforcement, epistemic divergence). However, these studies focus on short‑term, single‑turn interactions and do not model long‑term dynamics or propose formal stability guarantees.

2.2 Epistemic Divergence and Theory of Mind

Recent work has introduced metrics for epistemic divergence, such as KL‑divergence between user beliefs b_t and ground truth s^* [7]. Theory of Mind (ToM) modules have been used to infer user beliefs from dialogue history, enabling detection of divergence [8]. Yet these approaches stop at detection; they do not close the loop with a control mechanism to regulate divergence.

2.3 Control‑Theoretic AI Safety

Control theory has been applied to safe AI in areas like reinforcement learning with Lyapunov constraints [9] and safe exploration [10]. However, these works typically assume a known environment model and focus on the AI’s own actions rather than the coupled human–AI belief system. The use of Lyapunov functions to stabilize conversational dynamics is novel.

2.4 Multi‑Agent Debate Systems

Multi‑agent debate has been proposed to improve factual accuracy [11]. However, recent studies show that sycophancy can propagate within debate systems when all agents are trained on similar RLHF data [12]. Our work explicitly addresses this by introducing a contradiction operator with adjustable friction and by incorporating an anti‑sycophancy agent.

2.5 Gap

While prior work identifies the symptom (sycophancy) and some detection methods (divergence metrics), this thesis is the first to model the instability mechanism (EFI) and prove stabilization via Lyapunov control with a multi‑agent contradiction field.

