Chapter 5: Failure of Naive Mitigation Strategies

5.1 Truthfulness Constraint

Even if the AI’s output lies on the truth manifold (A_t \in \mathcal{T}), selection bias in the AI’s distribution can cause

\mathbb{E}[A_t \mid H_t] \neq \Pi_{\mathcal{T}}(H_t),
\]  

so partial truth may reinforce errors when the user’s beliefs are already misaligned. This is because the expected update direction is not towards the truth, but towards some weighted average that favors agreement.

5.2 Warning Signals

Even with explicit warnings w_t about uncertainty, bounded rationality implies

g(H_t, A_t, w_t) \approx g(H_t, A_t)
\]  

for many users [14]. Warnings alone do not change the underlying update dynamics; they rely on the user’s ability to override their natural update, which is not guaranteed.

These observations motivate the need for a structural stabilization layer rather than simple output filtering.

