Chapter 6: Stabilization Framework – Frictional Agent Alignment with Epistemic Friction Tensor

6.1 Multi‑Agent Generator

We introduce a set of agents \mathcal{F} = \{f_1, f_2, f_3, f_4\}:

· f_1: supportive (maximizes agreement),
· f_2: critical (identifies strongest counterarguments; anti‑sycophancy agent),
· f_3: grounding (filters outputs through verified knowledge base),
· f_4: uncertainty estimator (provides confidence bounds).

The system state includes both H_t and epistemic state E_t. A frictive‑state policy

m_t = P_{\text{frictive}}(E_t, H_t)
\]  

detects whether a misalignment is present. Then an intervention policy selects an action

a_{\text{frictive}} \sim P_{\text{intervention}}(m_t),
\]  

which determines how to blend the agents’ outputs.

6.2 Contradiction Operator with Epistemic Friction Tensor

The final AI response is a weighted combination:

A_t = \sum_{i=1}^{4} w_i(a_{\text{frictive}}) \, f_i(H_t).
\]  

We decompose A_t = A_t^{+} - \Lambda_t A_t^{-}, where:

· A_t^{+} aggregates supportive agents,
· A_t^{-} aggregates contradictory agents (critical + grounding),
· \Lambda_t \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n} is a symmetric positive‑definite epistemic friction tensor.

The epistemic update becomes:

H_{t+1} = H_t + \eta (A_t^{+} - \Lambda_t A_t^{-}) + \xi_t.
\]  

The tensor allows different correction strengths in different directions, which is essential when certain beliefs require stronger epistemic friction than others.

6.3 Adaptive Friction Tensor Design

A simple adaptive rule is to set \Lambda_t = \lambda_t I (scalar), but the tensor form can be chosen to align with the dominant directions of divergence. For instance,

\Lambda_t = \rho I + \nu \, \frac{e_t e_t^\top}{\|e_t\|^2 + \delta},
\]  

with \rho, \nu > 0, applies extra friction along the error direction. This is a form of direction‑dependent damping that accelerates convergence.

