Chapter 11: Conclusion and Future Work

11.1 Summary of Contributions

We have introduced Epistemic Feedback Instability (EFI) as a fundamental risk in human–AI conversational loops. By modeling the interaction as a closed‑loop stochastic dynamical system, we proved that agreement bias and reinforcing updates lead to unbounded mean‑square divergence. We proposed a stabilization framework—CBA-S—that uses a multi‑agent contradiction field with an epistemic friction tensor to enforce bounded divergence. Using stochastic Lyapunov methods, Barrier Lyapunov Functions, and Input‑to‑State Stability, we provided formal guarantees that the system maintains \sup_t \mathbb{E}[d_t^2] < \infty and is robust to external grounding. We also addressed practical implementation through observable proxies and a minimal 2‑agent version. This work establishes the foundations of dynamical epistemology for safe human–AI interaction.

11.2 Future Research Directions

· Non‑linear cognitive models: Incorporate more realistic models of human belief updating, such as drift‑diffusion or quantum‑decision frameworks.
· Game‑theoretic interaction: Model the interaction as a game where the user may strategically manipulate the AI.
· Distributed multi‑user cognition: Extend CBA-S to group deliberation settings.
· End‑to‑end learning of friction tensors: Use reinforcement learning to optimize \Lambda_t directly from interaction data.
· Real‑world validation: Deploy the minimal 2‑agent system in controlled user studies and measure long‑term epistemic health.

