Appendix B: Mathematical Background

This appendix collects the definitions and concepts used throughout the thesis for reference.

B.1 Stochastic Dynamical Systems

A discrete‑time stochastic process \{X_t\}_{t\ge 0} on a probability space (\Omega,\mathcal{F},\mathbb{P}) is defined by the update

X_{t+1} = F(X_t, \xi_t),

where \xi_t is an i.i.d. sequence of random vectors. The conditional expectation \mathbb{E}[\,\cdot\mid X_t] is used to define stability concepts.

B.2 Lyapunov Functions

A function V: \mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0} is a stochastic Lyapunov function if there exist class \mathcal{K} functions \alpha_1,\alpha_2,\alpha_3 such that

\alpha_1(\|x\|) \le V(x) \le \alpha_2(\|x\|), \qquad \mathbb{E}[V(X_{t+1})\mid X_t=x] - V(x) \le -\alpha_3(\|x\|).

This ensures mean‑square stability.

B.3 Barrier Lyapunov Function (BLF)

For a constrained state d_t = \|e_t\| < b, a BLF is a function that grows to infinity as d_t \to b. A typical choice is

V(x) = \log\frac{b^2}{b^2 - \|x\|^2}.

If the drift of V is negative when d_t approaches b, the constraint is never violated.

B.4 Input‑to‑State Stability (ISS)

A deterministic system x_{t+1} = f(x_t, u_t) is ISS if there exist \beta\in\mathcal{KL} and \gamma\in\mathcal{K} such that

\|x_t\| \le \beta(\|x_0\|, t) + \gamma(\sup_{0\le \tau\le t} \|u_\tau\|).

For stochastic systems, we consider the mean‑square version.

